            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Senator Douglas and the Opposition Press</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>It is clear that the Opposition party is beginning to notice and talk about
                    the inconsistency and lack of across-the-scale support for Senator Douglas among
                    Democrats, especially over his territorial policy. While the Vindicator opposes
                    Douglas's nomination as presidential candidate, it would no doubt support him
                    over any Black Republican candidate.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head/>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p>"...on the action of those States from which the prisoners are demanded,
                        would depend the revival or the total extinction of good feeling between the
                        two sections, and even the existence of the Union itself."</p>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Brown</ln>
                        <fn>John</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Douglas</ln>
                        <fn>Fred.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Smith</ln>
                        <fn>Geritt</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Wise</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Gov.</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>The papers found in Brown's possession after his capture demonstrate beyond
                    a doubt the existence of a northern conspiracy against slavery. The Vindicator
                    suggests that the states that are home to those complicit in the affair should
                    deliver up those absent co-conspirators for persecution in order to restore
                    harmony between the regions.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Trial of Farrar</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Farrar</ln>
                        <fn>William</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Vance</ln>
                        <fn>Michael</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Harman</ln>
                        <fn>William</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Gen.</pf>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Stuart</ln>
                        <fn>Briscoe</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Farrar is on trial for killing Vance, who had spoken improperly in front of
                    Farrar's wife, to which Farrar responded by hitting Vance and dislocating his
                    neck.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Admits It</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The New York Tribune admits that one of its agents (and a victim of the
                    Harper's Ferry insurrection) was corresponding for that paper.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Brown and Giddings</head>
                <origin>The Washington States</origin>
                <commentary>"Though Giddings denies having consulted Brown on the insurrection at
                    Harper's Ferry, it seems clear that he is guilty."</commentary>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Article gives evidence that Joshua Giddings had consulted John Brown before
                    the insurrection. Giddings should thus be convicted for aiding Brown.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>2</column>
                <head>Hitherto, Liberty and Religion have maintained...</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p>"An invading army lately penetrated into our midst, with the hope that
                        thousands of discontented slaves would flock to their standard at the first
                        beat of the drum--NOT ONE ANSWERED THE SUMMONS."</p>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Article examines the insurrection at Harper's Ferry, essentially condemning
                    the use of violence to try to shake (uselessly) a deeply entrenched social
                    order. It also comments on the futility of trying to get slaves who are content
                    with their lot to revolt.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>The Staunton Lyceum</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>The Staunton Lyceum will meet Monday night.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>Fred Douglass Fled</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Fred Douglass has failed to show up in New York for an appointment; it is
                    rumored that he has fled to Canada.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>A Swindling Imposter</head>
                <origin>Wm. T. League &amp; Co.</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Bright</ln>
                        <fn>John P.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Wise</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Gov.</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Article warns the public in general and newspapermen in particular about
                    John Bright, who pretended to have a letter of recommendation from Gov. Wise
                    about his abilities as a printer and who claimed, falsely, to have worked for
                    the Staunton Vindicator. He borrowed money from Wm. T. League &amp; Co. and
                    took off, never to be seen or heard from since. The article then describes
                him.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>Funeral of One of the Colored Victims</head>
                <origin>Alexandria Gazette</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Haywood</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Mr.</pf>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Moore</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Col.</pf>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Washington</ln>
                        <fn>B.B.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Major</pf>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Holliday</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Mr.</pf>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Brown</ln>
                        <fn>John</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Cook</ln>
                        <fn/>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Mr.</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Haywood, one of Harper's Ferry's black victims, was buried in Alexandria
                    with ceremony.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head/>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p>Mr. Tom Marshall, our gentlemanly and efficient Constable, who is so very much given to nabbing 
                        others, came near being nabbed himself the other evening.-- He most incautiously invaded the 
                        "beat" of a black Bear, somewhere between this place and Greenville, and was only saved from his 
                        lethal embraces by the speed of his horse, which last, however, did not escape ignominious 
                        wounds on his rump.</p>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Marshall</ln>
                        <fn>Tom</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Marshall, Staunton's constable, almost lost his life to a black bear, but
                    his horse saved him!</summary>
                <note>aubrowser/rvoct59.html#10.28a</note>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>Arrested</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>John E. Cook, one of the fanatics at Harper's Ferry, was arrested in
                    Pennsylvania. Gov. Wise requested that he be sent to Virginia.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>The Baltimore Republican...</head>
                <origin>The Baltimore Republican</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Buvlingame</ln>
                        <fn>Andson</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Davis</ln>
                        <fn>Henry</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Davis</ln>
                        <fn>French</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>The Baltimore Republican announces a meeting of all opponents of
                slavery.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>Legal Counsel for Brown</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Black Republican sympathizers of Brown in Massachusetts are raising money
                    for his counsel.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>From Washington--Fight Between Congressional Candidates</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Hagner and Hughes, opposing candidates from Maryland, may fight a duel. The
                    government has decided not to strengthen guards at federal arsenals and armories
                    after Harper's Ferry.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>5</column>
                <head>Ossawattomie Brown</head>
                <origin>Cleveland Democrat</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Article discusses Brown's exploits before Harper's Ferry, including
                    stealing slaves and running them to Canada.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>5</column>
                <head>The Chevalier Webb on Slavery</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>General James Watson Webb has suddenly denounced Republicanism, stating
                    that he devoutly believes in slavery.</summary>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>6</column>
                <head>The Pulpit and the Rebellion</head>
                <origin/>
                <commentary/>
                <transcript>
                    <p/>
                </transcript>
                <trailer/>
